metadata.title: Ryan Navion
aws::graph::propositions: Military Variants of the Ryan Navion Aircraft
L-17A was the military designation for NA-154s delivered to the United States Army.
83 L-17A aircraft were built.
L-17A was re-designated as U-18A in 1962.
QL-17A was a variant of the L-17A.
Six L-17As were modified by TEMCO as remote-controlled drones.
The QL-17A drones were for the United States Air Force.
L-17B was the military designation for Ryan-built Navion As delivered to the United States Army.
163 L-17B aircraft were built.
L-17B was re-designated as U-18B in 1962.
L-17C was a modified version of the L-17A.
L-17C had improved brakes compared to the L-17A.
L-17C had increased fuel capacity compared to the L-17A.
35 L-17A aircraft were modified into L-17C aircraft by Ryan.
L-17C was re-designated as U-18C in 1962.
XL-17D consisted of three former XL-22As for evaluation.
XL-22A was the designation for two Ryan-built Navion Bs for the United States Army.
XL-22A was re-designated as XL-17D.
U-18A was the designation for former L-17As after 1962.
U-18B was the designation for former L-17Bs after 1962.

text:
### Military
L-17A
Military designation for NA-154s delivered to the United States Army, 83 built, re-designated U-18A in 1962.
QL-17A
Six L-17As modified by TEMCO as remote-controlled drones for the United States Air Force.
L-17B
Military designation for Ryan-built Navion As delivered to the U.S.Army, 163 built, re-designated U-18B in 1962.
L-17C
L-17As modified by Ryan with improved brakes and increased fuel capacity, 35 modified, re-designated U-18C in 1962.
XL-17D
Three former XL-22As for evaluation.
XL-22A
Two Ryan-built Navion Bs for the U.S.Army, re-designated XL-17D.
U-18A
Former L-17As re-designated in 1962.
U-18B
Former L-17Bs re-designated in 1962.
